               <note>
                  
                  <ab type="history">Dawāro was one of the seven Muslim trading states of the southern<placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop"/>
                     which corresponds to the present day <placeName ref="LOC6874Arsi"/>. It is bordered with <placeName ref="LOC1743Bale"/>Sultanate in south, 
                     Dawāro was separated from it by the <placeName ref="LOC6095WabiSa"/> river and bordered on <placeName ref="LOC3921Ifat"/> on the right bank of  
                     <placeName ref="LOC1617Awas"/>. In the east, it reached the edge of the <placeName ref="LOC1274Afar"/> lowlands, in th south-west it bordered on the small principalities of 
                     <placeName ref="LOC5581Sarha"/>and <placeName ref="LOC1499Arabab"/>. In Ethiopic chronicles it appears first in that of 
                     <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName><persName ref="PRS1854Amdase"/>. Acccording to this source, he subdued Dawāro  together with 
                     <placeName ref="LOC3921Ifat"/>,  <placeName ref="LOC5581Sarha"/> and <placeName ref="LOC1743Bale"/> in the war of <date>1332</date>, 
                     when it was ruled by a governor
                     called <persName ref="PRS5193haydara"/>. After the victory of  <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName><persName ref="PRS1854Amdase"/> in <date>1332</date>, 
                     Dawāro  became a strong hold of the Christian empire. Following the defeat of the Christian emepror, <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>, 
                     <persName ref="PRS6229LebnaDe"/>, in <date>1529</date>, Dawāro came under the domain of the Muslim territoy. It was ruled first by the son of 
                     <persName ref="PRS1522Ahmadb"/>, <persName ref="PRS7506Nasraddi"></persName> during the first year of the reign of  <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName> 
                     <persName ref="PRS4428Galawdew"/>. After the death of <persName ref="PRS7506Nasraddi"/> in <date>1542</date>, 
                     Dawāro was ruled by one of the a great war lord of  <persName ref="PRS1522Ahmadb"/>, <persName ref="PRS1076Abbasb"/> who was later defeated and killed by 
                     <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName><persName ref="PRS4428Galawdew"/>. Then after, <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName><persName ref="PRS4428Galawdew"/> appointed 
                     <persName  ref="PRS3984Fanuel"/>, one of his principal commanders as governor of  Dawāro and the region depend on it. 
                     The chronicle of <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName><persName ref="PRS4428Galawdew"/>describes Dawāro a blessed land that flows milk and honey 
                     which represents it was the most fertile and suitable land for agricultural activities in medieval time. Since the half of 16th century, it was devastated and overrun by the<persName ref="ETH1973Oromo"/>
                     and it became the major settlement of them.
                  </ab>
                  
                  
